    <h3 style="color: white; margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Educational Deep Dive: Understanding Aspect Ratio and Resolution</h3>
    <p style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.8); line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        Resizing an image isn't just about changing numbers; it's about maintaining the <strong>Aspect Ratio</strong>. This is the proportional relationship between width and height. If you change one without the other, your image gets stretched or squashed, losing its natural look.
    </p>
    <p style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.8); line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        You also need to keep <strong>Resolution</strong> (measured in PPI or DPI) in mind. A larger physical size requires more pixels to stay sharp. By using the Webtigo Resizer, you can lock your aspect ratio to ensure your photos always look perfect, whether you're scaling them down for a profile picture or up for a presentation.
    </p>

    <h3 style="color: white; margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">The Difference Between Compressing and Resizing
    </h3>
    <p style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.8); line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        Before we dive in, let's clear up a massive internet misconception:
    </p>
    <ul style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.8); line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 1rem; padding-left: 20px;">
        <li><strong>Image Compressor:</strong> Changes the file size (Megabytes to Kilobytes) by removing hidden data,
            but the picture stays the same physical dimensions on your screen.</li>
        <li><strong>Image Resizer:</strong> Changes the dimensions (Pixels). It literally alters how tall and how wide
            the image is on your screen.</li>
    </ul>
    <p style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.8); line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        The Webtigo Image Resizer lets you stretch, shrink, or perfectly scale your photos to fit into any digital frame
        you need. You simply upload your image, type in your desired <a href="/resizer?w=100&h=100" target="_blank"
            style="color: var(--primary); text-decoration: underline;">Width and Height</a>, and hit generate. It is
        that easy!
    </p>

